
+ According to ...

  https://tex.stackexchange.com/questions/582531/differences-between-dvi-files-created-via-lualatex-and-dvi-files-created-via-p

  ... recent luatex will generate DVI that contains font **file paths** 
  in fontdef ops and **glyph IDs** in set ops !!!!

  (i.e., closer to XeTeX and MUCH easier to work with for 'xdvir')

  Anecdotally, TeX Live on Ubuntu 22.04 produces exactly that sort
  of output !!!

  This is conditional on luaotfload version v3.15
  [See page 4 of 
   https://mirror.cse.unsw.edu.au/pub/CTAN/macros/luatex/generic/luaotfload/luaotfload-latex.pdf]

  AND THIS is the commit ...

  https://github.com/latex3/luaotfload/commit/7473c3013d955c86c4b82b06c876d464be503e81

  ... which says this ...

-- When writing DVI files, we can't assume that the DVI reader has access to our
-- font dictionaries, so we need an independent representation for our glyphs. The
-- approach we chose in coordination with the dvisvgm author is to create a DVI font
-- name which indicates the font filename and some essential backend parameters
-- (especially otential extend, shrink, embolden, etc. factors) and then use GIDs in
-- the page stream.

  ... which suggests that the change to font file names occurred at the same
  time as the change to glyph IDs (!!!)

  NOTE the quoted comment at the top of the SE post above about luatex
  dvi output not being important, BUT the discussion suggests that
  there are others besides me interested in playing with luatex's dvi
  files (e.g., the dvi-decode [https://github.com/matjp/dvi-decode] guy)

  Here is a link to a(n unofficial and already slightly out of date)
  description of the luatex dvi font def format ...

  https://tug.org/pipermail/dvipdfmx/2021-January/000168.html


+ Work on font-api.R to make it independent of TTX implementation
  (e.g., does 'systemfonts' refer to glyphs by name or by index?
         what do other libraries do?)

  This impacts on luatex.R and uptex.R - need to shift that conversion
  of UNICODE to glyph names into TTX implementation

+ NOTE that systemfonts::match_font() basically does ...

  fc-match :family=<family>,weight=<bold?700:400>,slant=<italic>

  ... so it is NOT flexible enough (ditto C interface)
  
  => we still need to use 'fc-match' (and rely on 'fontconfig' install)
     directly

  => need a solution for Windows!!!

  Install fontconfig on windows ... ?

  https://lists.freedesktop.org/archives/fontconfig/2007-October/002686.html

+ How about a user option to specify particular mappings like

  "xdvir.uptex.ryumin-substitute"

  Ryumin -> ipamp.ttf ?

+ NOTE that systemfonts::glyph_info() is almost useful,
  BUT it only allows 'glyphs' to be given as character values
  NOT as integer glyph ids (ditto C interface)
  (SO no use after all)

  BUT maybe when an engine generates DVI with UNICODE chars, could use
  'systemfonts' to loop up glyph metrics ?

  Could feed my needs into future development of 'systemfonts' ?

